Precision on built in constant is maximum to applicable numeric type.
Assignment is value based. I.e 'y = 0; x =1; y = x' ends with both y & x being assigned to 1.
Matrix literals are in the form [element, element; element, element]
Map literals are int the form [key-value, key-value, key-value].  the '-' can be used to distinguish from matrix literals.
Collection elements can be accessed by index collection[0]
Unordered collections can be accessed by index too, but index permenance is never guaranteed.
Map elements can be accessed by map(key)
Currently only 1 error exists whenever anything bad happens. that is error code 1, unknown error.
All purely numeric types (include 'num' in short for of name), are 64 bits long. If complex that gives 32+32 for each part.
Concatatenation trumps element wise addition
For operands like diff, which can return both a scalar and a collection, the return depends on the type it is assigned to, defaulting to the simpler type.
There is both compile and run-time type checkign

General Design Philosophy:
This language is meant to offer high level abstraction, allowing a user with little to no-understanding of quantum mechanics, to exploit them.
Simultaneously, this language allows for low level interactions with quantum systems.
Furthermore, while too simplistic for classical programming uses, and containing minimal types, there is an aim to offer a comprehensive package of mathematical operands for easy calculations.
On the technical side, no lower level operation is ever able to be done in two equivalent ways, with the except of quantum circuit design.
The language is designed to be readable for those with applicable sceintific and mathematical knowledge, with little to no programming experience.


